00:13:29,600 --> 00:13:31,920
But to put units in,

290
00:13:31,920 --> 00:13:34,850
which is the same as square root

291
00:13:34,850 --> 00:13:37,780
of c plus v over c minus v.

292
00:13:39,280 --> 00:13:40,420
What do you think happens if

293
00:13:40,420 --> 00:13:41,560
you're going in the other direction?

294
00:13:43,220 --> 00:13:44,960
If I was going in the other direction?

295
00:13:46,660 --> 00:13:49,090
You would just change the sign of

296
00:13:49,090 --> 00:13:51,520
the velocity from plus v to minus v.

297
00:13:51,600 --> 00:13:53,240
That's just going in the other direction,

298
00:13:53,240 --> 00:13:53,960
minus v.

299
00:13:54,320 --> 00:13:55,930
And you would get square root of

300
00:13:55,930 --> 00:13:57,540
c plus v over c minus v.

301
00:14:04,060 --> 00:14:06,160
And now this is less than 1.

302
00:14:07,040 --> 00:14:08,600
So if you're shooting against

303
00:14:08,600 --> 00:14:10,160
the direction of the light ray,

304
00:14:10,160 --> 00:14:12,000
you see a shorter wavelength.

305
00:14:12,480 --> 00:14:15,160
If you're moving along the light ray,

306
00:14:15,160 --> 00:14:16,340
you see a longer wavelength.

307
00:14:17,280 --> 00:14:19,030
And what happens if your velocity

308
00:14:19,030 --> 00:14:20,780
gets up near the speed of light?

309
00:14:22,180 --> 00:14:23,640
Let's say this one over here.

310
00:14:23,740 --> 00:14:25,920
If your velocity gets up near the speed of light,

311
00:14:25,920 --> 00:14:27,520
then the wavelength is going to be

312
00:14:27,520 --> 00:14:29,260
bigger and bigger and bigger.

313
00:14:29,680 --> 00:14:30,540
And eventually,

314
00:14:30,540 --> 00:14:32,380
if you're moving with a light ray,

315
00:14:32,380 --> 00:14:33,380
if you could,

316
00:14:33,380 --> 00:14:35,320
the wavelength would look infinite.

317
00:14:36,060 --> 00:14:36,200
OK.

318
00:14:37,320 --> 00:14:38,400
There's another way to...

319
00:14:38,400 --> 00:14:38,640
Yeah,

320
00:14:38,640 --> 00:14:39,320
that's fine.

321
00:14:39,480 --> 00:14:40,240
Let's leave it that way.

322
00:14:40,420 --> 00:14:40,900
OK.

323
00:14:42,020 --> 00:14:42,500
Good.

324
00:14:44,160 --> 00:14:44,820
All right.

325
00:14:44,840 --> 00:14:46,040
If there are no further questions,

326
00:14:46,040 --> 00:14:49,860
we will start tonight's lecture 10 minutes late.

327
00:14:53,960 --> 00:14:55,040
Fields and particles.

328
00:14:55,660 --> 00:14:56,940
Now in quantum mechanics,

329
00:14:56,940 --> 00:14:57,500
fields and particles are just like a circle.

330
00:14:57,520 --> 00:14:58,860
Fields and particles are the same thing.

331
00:14:59,680 --> 00:15:01,500
But we're not doing quantum mechanics.

332
00:15:02,420 --> 00:15:03,400
For us here,

333
00:15:03,400 --> 00:15:06,660
fields are fields and particles are particles.

334
00:15:07,100 --> 00:15:09,100
I won't say never that twain will meet,

335
00:15:09,100 --> 00:15:09,840
because they will meet.

336
00:15:09,920 --> 00:15:10,580
They will meet tonight.

337
00:15:11,700 --> 00:15:13,820
But they are not the same thing.

338
00:15:15,380 --> 00:15:16,340
In particular,

339
00:15:16,340 --> 00:15:20,560
we want to ask the question if a

340
00:15:20,560 --> 00:15:24,780
field affects a particle in a certain way.

341
00:15:24,940 --> 00:15:25,560
For example,

342
00:15:25,560 --> 00:15:27,500
by creating forces in the field.

343
00:15:27,520 --> 00:15:27,680
So,

344
00:15:27,680 --> 00:15:29,380
if there are forces on it that accelerate it,

345
00:15:29,380 --> 00:15:30,060
or whatever they do,

346
00:15:30,060 --> 00:15:32,490
must it not also be the

347
00:15:32,490 --> 00:15:34,920
case that the particle affects the field?

348
00:15:35,780 --> 00:15:36,260
Well,

349
00:15:36,260 --> 00:15:36,960
why do I say that?

350
00:15:37,020 --> 00:15:38,160
Why does it have to be the case?

351
00:15:38,280 --> 00:15:38,500
Why,

352
00:15:38,500 --> 00:15:39,760
if A affects B,

353
00:15:39,760 --> 00:15:42,960
does B necessarily have to affect A?

354
00:15:44,000 --> 00:15:47,420
And that's built into the idea of action.

355
00:15:47,600 --> 00:15:49,660
That's built into the action principle,

356
00:15:49,660 --> 00:15:51,240
or into the Lagrangian principle.

357
00:15:51,780 --> 00:15:53,380
We can see it in a very...

358
00:15:53,380 --> 00:15:54,680
In a simple context.

359
00:15:54,680 --> 00:15:56,840
It's also called action and reaction.

360
00:15:58,420 --> 00:15:59,600
It's a basic idea.

361
00:15:59,760 --> 00:16:00,840
If A affects B,

362
00:16:00,840 --> 00:16:02,180
then B will affect A.

363
00:16:02,960 --> 00:16:03,480
So,

364
00:16:03,480 --> 00:16:06,130
a simple example of it is

365
00:16:06,130 --> 00:16:08,780
to suppose that you had two coordinates.

366
00:16:09,560 --> 00:16:10,080
Now,

367
00:16:10,080 --> 00:16:11,720
you could have any number of coordinates,

368
00:16:11,720 --> 00:16:14,630
but let's just suppose for the

369
00:16:14,630 --> 00:16:17,540
moment two coordinates and an action principle.

370
00:16:18,120 --> 00:16:18,640
So,

371
00:16:18,640 --> 00:16:20,240
let's call the coordinates x and y.

372
00:16:22,740 --> 00:16:23,700
And the Lagrangian is going

373
00:16:23,700 --> 00:16:24,660
to depend on the action principle.

374
00:16:24,680 --> 00:16:24,680
So,

375
00:16:24,680 --> 00:16:25,500
the Lagrangian is going to depend on x and y,

376
00:16:25,500 --> 00:16:26,860
and x dot and y dot.

377
00:16:27,940 --> 00:16:29,640
x and y do not have

378
00:16:29,640 --> 00:16:31,340
to stand for the orthogonal coordinates,

379
00:16:31,340 --> 00:16:33,460
Cartesian coordinates of anything.

380
00:16:34,060 --> 00:16:35,180
They're just two coordinates.

381
00:16:36,120 --> 00:16:38,940
And the Lagrangian depends on all of these.

382
00:16:40,560 --> 00:16:41,040
Now,

383
00:16:41,040 --> 00:16:43,500
one possibility is that the Lagrangian

384
00:16:43,500 --> 00:16:45,960
is simply a sum of two terms.

385
00:16:46,040 --> 00:16:48,800
The Lagrangian for x and x dot,

386
00:16:48,800 --> 00:16:52,800
plus the Lagrangian for y and y dot.

387
00:16:52,800 --> 00:16:54,540
A different Lagrangian.

388
00:16:54,620 --> 00:16:56,320
I'll just continue to call it L.

389
00:16:56,560 --> 00:16:57,600
Might be the same,

390
00:16:57,600 --> 00:16:58,300
might be different.

391
00:16:59,080 --> 00:17:00,580
If this is the case,

392
00:17:00,580 --> 00:17:04,319
and you look at the equation of motion for x.

393
00:17:04,980 --> 00:17:05,920
Let's write it down.

394
00:17:08,280 --> 00:17:08,760
Then,

395
00:17:08,760 --> 00:17:12,750
that equation of motion will involve d by dt of partial of L with

396
00:17:12,750 --> 00:17:16,740
respect to x dot is equal to partial of L with respect to x.

397
00:17:16,880 --> 00:17:18,700
And y won't get into it altogether.

398
00:17:20,260 --> 00:17:20,740
Likewise,

399
00:17:20,740 --> 00:17:22,780
if you write the equation of motion for y.

400
00:17:22,780 --> 00:17:24,200
x doesn't get into it.

401
00:17:24,640 --> 00:17:26,079
And so in this case,

402
00:17:26,079 --> 00:17:27,520
x doesn't affect y.

403
00:17:27,680 --> 00:17:28,840
y doesn't affect x.

404
00:17:29,020 --> 00:17:32,580
What can you say if you

405
00:17:32,580 --> 00:17:36,140
know that y does affect x?

406
00:17:36,700 --> 00:17:40,240
That tells you that the Lagrangian must be more complicated,

407
00:17:40,240 --> 00:17:44,110
and there must be things in it

408
00:17:44,110 --> 00:17:47,980
which somehow affect both x and y.

409
00:17:48,700 --> 00:17:49,860
For example,

410
00:17:49,860 --> 00:17:51,500
here's a Lagrangian.

411
00:17:55,260 --> 00:17:57,100
x dot squared over 2

412
00:17:57,100 --> 00:17:58,940
plus y dot squared over 2.

413
00:17:59,080 --> 00:17:59,540
So far,

414
00:17:59,540 --> 00:18:00,600
they're completely independent.

415
00:18:01,260 --> 00:18:04,520
You could have a potential energy for x,

416
00:18:04,520 --> 00:18:05,520
or minus.

417
00:18:06,060 --> 00:18:08,020
And maybe another potential energy,

418
00:18:08,020 --> 00:18:08,760
v prime,

419
00:18:08,760 --> 00:18:09,620
for y.

420
00:18:11,080 --> 00:18:11,900
So far,

421
00:18:11,900 --> 00:18:13,220
it's just a sum of two terms.

422
00:18:13,340 --> 00:18:15,340
An x term and a y term.

423
00:18:15,960 --> 00:18:17,820
x and y are not going to affect each other.

424
00:18:18,080 --> 00:18:19,880
What do you need to do if

425
00:18:19,880 --> 00:18:21,680
you want to see them affect each other?

426
00:18:21,680 --> 00:18:24,870
Put something in addition to the Lagrangian which involves both

427
00:18:24,870 --> 00:18:28,060
x and y in a way that you can't unravel it.

428
00:18:28,180 --> 00:18:28,980
For example,

429
00:18:28,980 --> 00:18:30,020
just x times y.

430
00:18:31,840 --> 00:18:33,320
If you have x times y,

431
00:18:33,320 --> 00:18:37,580
then the equation of motion for x will involve y.

432
00:18:38,580 --> 00:18:41,380
And the equation of motion for y will involve x.

433
00:18:42,020 --> 00:18:44,680
If you have them both in the Lagrangian in

434
00:18:44,680 --> 00:18:47,340
a way which is coupled together in this way,

435
00:18:47,480 --> 00:18:49,440
there's no way that it's possible

436
00:18:49,440 --> 00:18:51,400
that one can affect the other.

437
00:18:51,400 --> 00:18:54,120
Without the other affecting the one.

438
00:18:55,340 --> 00:18:56,780
So that's as simple as that.

439
00:18:56,880 --> 00:19:00,060
That is why if A affects B,

440
00:19:00,060 --> 00:19:01,000
B affects A.

441
00:19:01,780 --> 00:19:02,300
Okay.

442
00:19:02,800 --> 00:19:04,260
Now let's come to the issue,

443
00:19:04,260 --> 00:19:06,100
let's talk about particles and fields.

444
00:19:06,820 --> 00:19:10,130
We talked a little bit last time about how

445
00:19:10,130 --> 00:19:13,440
a field might affect the motion of a particle.

446
00:19:14,220 --> 00:19:15,880
That was just a simple model,

447
00:19:15,880 --> 00:19:17,420
but we'll go back to it.

448
00:19:18,240 --> 00:19:19,420
Let's go back to it.

449
00:19:20,320 --> 00:19:20,850
Talk about how a field might

450
00:19:20,850 --> 00:19:21,380
affect the motion of a particle.

451
00:19:21,400 --> 00:19:23,260
How the field affects the particle motion.

452
00:19:23,480 --> 00:19:26,320
And then come back and ask how the particle,

453
00:19:26,320 --> 00:19:27,820
the presence of the particle,

454
00:19:27,820 --> 00:19:28,840
affects the field.

455
00:19:32,220 --> 00:19:36,680
This is very much the analog of electric

456
00:19:36,680 --> 00:19:41,140
and magnetic fields affecting the motion of charged particles.

457
00:19:41,260 --> 00:19:44,230
And charged particles creating

458
00:19:44,230 --> 00:19:47,200
and modifying the electromagnetic field.

459
00:19:47,540 --> 00:19:48,560
For example,

460
00:19:48,560 --> 00:19:51,380
just by having a charged particle creates a coolant.

461
00:19:51,380 --> 00:19:52,440
A coolant field and so forth.

462
00:19:53,100 --> 00:19:56,160
And those are not two independent things.

463
00:19:56,640 --> 00:19:59,100
They come from the same Lagrangian.

464
00:20:00,100 --> 00:20:02,300
So let's work out this example.

465
00:20:02,700 --> 00:20:03,440
All right.

466
00:20:03,480 --> 00:20:06,480
So let's begin with,

467
00:20:06,480 --> 00:20:08,440
let's suppose first of all

468
00:20:08,440 --> 00:20:10,400
that there is some field phi.

469
00:20:11,960 --> 00:20:13,820
Phi depends on x and t.

470
00:20:16,140 --> 00:20:18,590
For the moment we forget about how it

471
00:20:18,590 --> 00:20:21,040
got to have the value that it has.

472
00:20:22,220 --> 00:20:24,820
Somebody solved some equations for phi and found

473
00:20:24,820 --> 00:20:27,420
out that phi of x and t has a,

474
00:20:27,420 --> 00:20:29,440
or measured phi of x and t.

475
00:20:29,860 --> 00:20:32,080
And it had some specific form.

476
00:20:32,460 --> 00:20:33,830
Phi of x might be a wave

477
00:20:33,830 --> 00:20:35,200
or it might not be a wave.

478
00:20:38,120 --> 00:20:41,400
How does that affect the motion of a particle?

479
00:20:41,440 --> 00:20:42,120
And for that,

480
00:20:42,120 --> 00:20:43,480
we're not going to ask

481
00:20:43,480 --> 00:20:44,840
about the dynamics of phi now.

482
00:20:44,920 --> 00:20:48,540
We're going to ask for the Lagrangian for the particle.

483
00:20:49,040 --> 00:20:50,880
This is the particle Lagrangian.

484
00:20:52,620 --> 00:20:57,480
So let's remember what it is to begin with.

485
00:20:57,720 --> 00:20:58,800
To begin with,

486
00:20:58,800 --> 00:21:05,360
it contains minus m times the square

487
00:21:05,360 --> 00:21:11,920
root of 1 minus x dot squared.

488
00:21:12,200 --> 00:21:12,800
What was this?

489
00:21:13,160 --> 00:21:15,220
This was the term in the

490
00:21:15,220 --> 00:21:17,280
Lagrangian that corresponded to an action

491
00:21:17,280 --> 00:21:19,320
which just added up all

492
00:21:19,320 --> 00:21:21,360
the proper times along the line.

493
00:21:21,380 --> 00:21:22,940
Along the little segments of a path.

494
00:21:24,140 --> 00:21:25,420
Multiplied by minus m.

495
00:21:26,400 --> 00:21:28,380
The integral of this Lagrangian,

496
00:21:28,380 --> 00:21:28,960
let's write it out.

497
00:21:29,020 --> 00:21:30,320
Let's write the integral dt,

498
00:21:30,320 --> 00:21:31,360
that's the action.

499
00:21:31,980 --> 00:21:34,840
That's the integral dt of this.

500
00:21:35,240 --> 00:21:38,100
And this is the same as minus

501
00:21:38,100 --> 00:21:40,960
m times the integral of the proper times

502
00:21:40,960 --> 00:21:43,140
from one end of the trajectory to another.

503
00:21:43,400 --> 00:21:43,700
Alright,

504
00:21:43,700 --> 00:21:48,160
so that's the ordinary Lagrangian for a particle.

505
00:21:48,280 --> 00:21:49,920
But that doesn't have anything in it

506
00:21:49,920 --> 00:21:54,220
in which the field affects the particle.

507
00:21:54,600 --> 00:21:56,100
So let's put in something for the field.

508
00:21:56,180 --> 00:21:57,000
A simple thing.

509
00:21:57,060 --> 00:21:58,260
The simplest thing we can think of.

510
00:21:58,320 --> 00:21:59,940
The simplest thing I can think of.

511
00:21:59,980 --> 00:22:01,040
Let me move this a little bit.

512
00:22:01,680 --> 00:22:05,580
And let me put minus m plus phi.

513
00:22:05,940 --> 00:22:08,090
Now phi is a function

514
00:22:08,090 --> 00:22:10,240
of position and time in general.

515
00:22:10,860 --> 00:22:12,620
So it's a function of x and t.

516
00:22:13,460 --> 00:22:14,900
But we're imagining for the

517
00:22:14,900 --> 00:22:16,340
moment that it's a known function

518
00:22:16,340 --> 00:22:18,540
of the coordinates of the particle.

519
00:22:18,540 --> 00:22:20,560
Times the same thing again.

520
00:22:21,000 --> 00:22:23,640
One minus x dot squared.

521
00:22:26,560 --> 00:22:28,660
That's the Lagrangian for a particle.

522
00:22:28,860 --> 00:22:31,060
I could work out the Euler Lagrange equations

523
00:22:31,060 --> 00:22:33,360
and find out how phi

524
00:22:33,360 --> 00:22:35,660
affects the motion of the particle.

525
00:22:36,720 --> 00:22:37,820
I'm going to do it,

526
00:22:37,820 --> 00:22:40,220
but I'm going to do it in the simplified approximation

527
00:22:40,220 --> 00:22:42,460
where the particle moves very slowly.

528
00:22:43,800 --> 00:22:45,140
Just as an illustration.

529
00:22:45,840 --> 00:22:47,180
I don't want to futz

530
00:22:47,180 --> 00:22:48,520
around with all the relativistic things.

531
00:22:48,540 --> 00:22:49,770
I want to get rid of the relativistic square

532
00:22:49,770 --> 00:22:51,000
roots of 1 minus v squared and so forth.

533
00:22:51,360 --> 00:22:52,820
This of course is v squared.

534
00:22:53,140 --> 00:22:54,670
And we could be thinking

535
00:22:54,670 --> 00:22:56,200
about a particle on a line.

536
00:22:56,380 --> 00:22:58,640
We don't need y and z in this.

537
00:22:58,820 --> 00:23:01,780
Just x is enough to illustrate the point.

538
00:23:02,460 --> 00:23:03,880
Particle moving in one dimension.

539
00:23:04,760 --> 00:23:07,060
Let me put back the speeds of light.

540
00:23:08,180 --> 00:23:10,340
It's useful to put back the speeds of light

541
00:23:10,340 --> 00:23:13,440
in order to see what the nonrelativistic limit is.

542
00:23:13,500 --> 00:23:16,500
The nonrelativistic limit is basically the limit

543
00:23:16,500 --> 00:23:19,020
in which the speed of light goes to infinity.

544
00:23:19,580 --> 00:23:21,250
When the speed of light is bigger

545
00:23:21,250 --> 00:23:22,920
than any other velocity in the problem,

546
00:23:23,060 --> 00:23:24,660
that's the nonrelativistic limit.

547
00:23:25,740 --> 00:23:26,940
The Newtonian limit.

548
00:23:28,960 --> 00:23:30,560
Lagrangian has units of energy.

549
00:23:31,600 --> 00:23:33,760
Mass does not have units of energy,

550
00:23:33,900 --> 00:23:35,380
unless the speed of light is 1.

551
00:23:36,280 --> 00:23:38,180
But if the speed of light is not 1,

552
00:23:38,260 --> 00:23:42,220
we put in minus mc squared.

553
00:23:42,560 --> 00:23:43,920
Now it has units of energy.

554
00:23:44,500 --> 00:23:46,380
Phi I'm just going to leave that way.

555
00:23:46,500 --> 00:23:47,560
The field is defined.

556
00:23:48,620 --> 00:23:49,060
Oh,

557
00:23:49,060 --> 00:23:50,380
let's put a constant in here.

558
00:23:50,400 --> 00:23:51,380
Let's put a g in here.

559
00:23:52,699 --> 00:23:56,660
This constant is a constant called a coupling constant.

560
00:23:57,480 --> 00:24:01,020
It measures the strength by which the field

561
00:24:01,020 --> 00:24:02,940
affects the motion of the particle.

562
00:24:03,100 --> 00:24:04,380
So let's put a g in here.

563
00:24:06,140 --> 00:24:07,980
g can be anything for the moment.

564
00:24:08,080 --> 00:24:09,000
We don't know what it is.

565
00:24:09,340 --> 00:24:11,020
It might have a c in it.

566
00:24:11,040 --> 00:24:11,920
It might not have a c in it.

567
00:24:11,940 --> 00:24:12,360
Not important.

568
00:24:12,680 --> 00:24:14,860
At the moment it's just g times phi.

569
00:24:14,860 --> 00:24:16,860
And phi depends on x and t.

570
00:24:19,720 --> 00:24:20,240
Now,

571
00:24:20,240 --> 00:24:21,140
let's exp...

572
00:24:21,140 --> 00:24:21,360
Oh,

573
00:24:21,360 --> 00:24:22,420
and of course,

574
00:24:23,540 --> 00:24:26,760
this is square root of 1 minus x dot squared

575
00:24:26,760 --> 00:24:28,380
over c squared.

576
00:24:30,300 --> 00:24:31,780
That's the Lagrangian with all

577
00:24:31,780 --> 00:24:33,260
the speeds of light in place.

578
00:24:33,940 --> 00:24:37,660
And now let's go to the nonrelativistic limit.

579
00:24:37,760 --> 00:24:39,000
The nonrelativistic limit,

580
00:24:39,160 --> 00:24:40,540
when c gets very large,

581
00:24:40,780 --> 00:24:42,780
we expand the square root.

582
00:24:43,120 --> 00:24:44,680
We expand the square root.

583
00:24:44,680 --> 00:24:46,140
Using the binomial expansion,

584
00:24:47,560 --> 00:24:50,860
1 minus a small number to the minus...

585
00:24:50,860 --> 00:24:51,980
to the one-half power,

586
00:24:52,320 --> 00:24:54,160
that just becomes...

587
00:24:54,680 --> 00:24:55,180
well,

588
00:24:55,180 --> 00:24:56,160
this thing becomes

589
00:24:56,680 --> 00:24:59,600
1 minus x dot squared

590
00:25:00,620 --> 00:25:03,140
over twice c squared.

591
00:25:04,440 --> 00:25:06,040
The twice comes...

592
00:25:06,040 --> 00:25:06,840
the one-half comes

593
00:25:07,440 --> 00:25:09,900
because this is something to the one-half power.

594
00:25:10,420 --> 00:25:12,980
I'm using that 1 plus epsilon

595
00:25:12,980 --> 00:25:14,220
or 1 minus epsilon

596
00:25:14,220 --> 00:25:15,060
in this case

597
00:25:15,760 --> 00:25:17,820
to the power one-half

598
00:25:17,820 --> 00:25:22,360
is just 1 minus one-half epsilon

599
00:25:22,980 --> 00:25:25,860
plus things which are really very much smaller

600
00:25:25,860 --> 00:25:28,880
because they will involve higher powers

601
00:25:28,880 --> 00:25:30,530
of the ratio of the

602
00:25:30,530 --> 00:25:32,180
velocity to the velocity of light.

603
00:25:32,820 --> 00:25:33,440
So,

604
00:25:33,440 --> 00:25:34,600
this is what we get.

605
00:25:35,990 --> 00:25:36,920
Plus tiny,

606
00:25:36,920 --> 00:25:37,620
tiny things.

607
00:25:37,720 --> 00:25:40,760
Let's erase this and write 1 minus x dot squared.

608
00:25:45,620 --> 00:25:46,980
Over 2c squared.

609
00:25:49,860 --> 00:25:51,060
Now we look at this

610
00:25:51,060 --> 00:25:53,860
and we try to find the biggest pieces,

611
00:25:54,060 --> 00:25:56,040
the pieces which are most important

612
00:25:56,040 --> 00:25:58,720
when the speed of light gets large.

613
00:25:59,060 --> 00:26:01,640
The obvious first piece is mc squared.

614
00:26:01,840 --> 00:26:03,560
Just mc squared times 1.

615
00:26:05,180 --> 00:26:07,740
But mc squared times 1 is just a number.

616
00:26:08,240 --> 00:26:09,580
It doesn't do anything.

617
00:26:09,760 --> 00:26:10,720
When you start different...

618
00:26:10,720 --> 00:26:12,140
It's a Lagrangian we're talking about.

619
00:26:12,400 --> 00:26:14,200
If you start differentiating it,

620
00:26:14,220 --> 00:26:17,720
with respect to position or velocity,

621
00:26:17,940 --> 00:26:18,620
it doesn't do anything.

622
00:26:18,780 --> 00:26:19,380
It's just a number.

623
00:26:19,900 --> 00:26:21,940
So that term is of no interest.

624
00:26:22,080 --> 00:26:23,820
Adding a constant in a Lagrangian

625
00:26:23,820 --> 00:26:26,240
doesn't have any effect on the equation of motion.

626
00:26:26,820 --> 00:26:30,560
So the mc squared times 1 is of no interest.

627
00:26:31,040 --> 00:26:36,660
The next term has the speed of light

628
00:26:36,660 --> 00:26:37,980
canceling altogether.

629
00:26:39,040 --> 00:26:41,080
So it's part of the limit

630
00:26:41,080 --> 00:26:43,560
in which the speed of light goes to infinity.

631
00:26:43,560 --> 00:26:44,740
And it survives.

632
00:26:45,260 --> 00:26:46,560
It survives that limit.

633
00:26:46,860 --> 00:26:51,040
So the next term is the product of mc squared

634
00:26:51,560 --> 00:26:54,060
times x dot squared over 2c squared.

635
00:26:54,180 --> 00:26:54,760
And that's familiar.

636
00:26:54,920 --> 00:26:59,040
That's x dot squared m over 2.

637
00:26:59,480 --> 00:27:01,240
The c squares have cancelled.

638
00:27:01,680 --> 00:27:04,720
And that's just a good old 1 half mv squared,

639
00:27:04,840 --> 00:27:06,520
the nonrelativistic kinetic energy.

640
00:27:07,980 --> 00:27:10,560
And what about this term?

641
00:27:10,720 --> 00:27:12,420
g phi times 1.

642
00:27:12,420 --> 00:27:14,260
That has no speeds of light in it,

643
00:27:14,360 --> 00:27:15,540
so it clearly survives.

644
00:27:16,740 --> 00:27:18,660
So we add minus.

645
00:27:18,740 --> 00:27:19,880
There's a minus sign here.

646
00:27:20,720 --> 00:27:24,660
Minus g phi of x and t.

647
00:27:25,420 --> 00:27:26,820
And that's all that there is

648
00:27:26,820 --> 00:27:28,360
when the particle is moving slowly.

649
00:27:30,580 --> 00:27:33,240
And we just compare that with,

